article.headline: 21-3 second-half run finished UTEP
article.linkText: Louisiana Tech reaches WAC final with little trouble
article.story:
FRESNO, Calif. (AP) -- After Amisha Carter and Trina Frierson
dominated yet another game, their coach was quick to credit the
guards who set up Louisiana Tech's dynamic duo.

Carter had 23 points and 12 rebounds, leading Louisiana
Tech (No. 6 ESPN/USA Today, No. 7 AP) to the finals of the Western Athletic Conference tournament with a 74-47 victory over UTEP on Friday.

Frierson scored 12 points for the Lady Techsters (26-2), who got
their 18th straight victory -- and the program's 850th win, the
second-highest total in NCAA history behind Tennessee.

Louisiana Tech made a 21-3 run in the second half, blowing out
yet another WAC opponent with a fast-break offense and suffocating
defense. The Lady Techsters have lost just two conference games in
their three seasons in the WAC, and coach Kurt Budke believes his
entire team deserves the credit.

"Amisha and Trina get a lot of the publicity, but they would
not put up the offensive numbers without our guards," Budke said.
"Our guards mean everything to us and give us balance. Everyone
does a good job of fitting into their established roles."

Budke singled out Erica Smith-Taylor and Tasha Crain for their
defense against UTEP's guards, a key to forcing the Miners' 21
turnovers.

Ingrid Goslin had 15 points and a season-high 13 rebounds for
the fourth-seeded Miners (15-13), who still finished their
resurgent season with their first winning record since 1998.

"In the second half, the press started to affect us, and we
turned the ball over too much," coach Keitha Green said. "I think
Louisiana Tech's level of play rose in the second half. I'm sure
they turned things up after halftime knowing that our girls were
into this game."

Louisiana Tech will face the winner of Rice's semifinal game
against Tulsa in the championship game Saturday at the new Save
Mart Center in Fresno. The Lady Techsters haven't lost since an
overtime defeat at Rice on Jan. 5.

Carter, the WAC's player of the year, scored nine points during
Louisiana Tech's decisive run. She went 9-for-11 from the field,
but just 5-for-14 on free throws.

Carter had 16 points in the second half, scoring from inside and
outside while the Lady Techsters held the Miners to 6-for-31
shooting in the second half.

UTEP's multinational team, which features players from six
countries, couldn't stand up to Louisiana Tech's execution and
speed. The Lady Techsters' guards made a handful of open-court
steals from UTEP guards Noni Wharemate and Vaida Zagurskyte, who
committed 12 turnovers.

"Our guards help us out and pressure other teams, allowing our
forwards opportunities to score," Carter said.
